@dusenberrymw  With respect to PyDML, my point is: Any API can only support subset of features that DML/PyDML supports. Any deviation will result in an ERROR, either thrown by that API or by the language layer of SystemML. The user will not care where the error comes from, just that he cannot use Python DSL for his task. If on the other hand, we want to support a given deviation, I would prefer to extend PyDML/DML itself than make Python DSL more complex. 

To be fair, two kinds of deviation that are not handled (but potentially possible): 
1. Subset of operations in loop to be pushed down to SystemML and subset of operations executed in Python as external builtin function. This requires traversal of AST and I decided not to go in that direction for now; instead I added a restriction that we cannot only push-down the subset of Python which maps to PyDML.
2. Handling of `sml` imports.

My understanding is that Imran's code didnot break down after adding `eval(H, W)` in the for loop, but was much slower. If that is not the case, then I agree with you, we need to understand the root cause of the problem.

@fschueler The signature of push-down loop is restricted. In current setup, we can examine the closure too by traversing the AST without a need for new construct. In my earlier PR, I had proposed adding a new construct `FOR` instead of `iterate` and it was not well-received.

Can be previewed here: http://deroneriksson.github.io/incubator-systemml/
Clicking the links from here will generate a description with a Section: http://deroneriksson.github.io/incubator-systemml/spark-mlcontext-programming-guide#matrix-data-conversions-and-performance

